svg:text.svg:tspan: A substance that reacts in a chemical reaction.
A graph that shows how the energy in a reaction changes as the reaction progresses.
A list of elements arranged in order of their reactivity.
The most reactive elements are at the top and the least reactive at the bottom.
A reaction where one substance is reduced and another is oxidised.
A reaction where electrons are gained or oxygen is lost.
The average mass of one atom of an element compared to
of the mass of one atom of carbon-12.
All the relative atomic masses () of the atoms in a compound added together.
A result that is repeatable and reproducible.
A resource that can be made at the same or similar rate as it’s being used.
A result that will come out the same if the experiment is repeated by
the same person using the same method and equipment.
The shortest repeating section of a polymer.
A result that will come out the same if someone different does the experiment,
or a slightly different method or piece of equipment is used.
The smallest change a measuring instrument can detect.
A reaction where the products of the reaction can themselves
react to produce the original reactants.
In chromatography, the ratio between the distance travelled by
a dissolved substance and the distance travelled by the solvent.
The chance that a hazard will cause harm.
A standard unit of measurement, recognised by scientists all over the world.
The first significant figure of a number is the first non-zero digit.
The second, third and fourth significant figures follow on immediately after it.
A way of separating a liquid out from a mixture if there are
large differences in the boiling points of the substances.
A molecule made up of only a few atoms held together by covalent bonds.
A substance is soluble if it dissolves in a particular solvent.
A substance dissolved in a solvent to make a solution.
A mixture made up of one substance (the solute) dissolved in another (the solvent).
A liquid in which another substance (a solute) can be dissolved.
The point the solvent has reached up the filter paper during paper chromatography.
The letter, or letters, in brackets that are placed after a substance in an equation to
show what physical state it’s in. E.g. gaseous carbon dioxide is shown as CO
In chromatography, the stationary phase is a solid or really thick liquid
where molecules are unable to move.
